The refined version of sequential search on a sorted array of numbers is a 
good algorithm if you search for small values because it doesn't take it long
to determine if it's found the value or not. In such cases it might perform better than binary search.

It does not appear as a good algorithm if you search for large values though,
because it might have to go through the whole array of numbers and that is costly (linear time complexity).

Binary search is a very consistent algorithm when it comes to the number of comparisons
it does. Whether it finds a certain value or not, the number of comparisons
is always logarithmic to the size of the array. Knowing this fact, this algorithm could be of very 
good use to the caller under certain circumstances.

Hash search (linear probing) is a good algorithm because it determines if it's found the value
almost instantly by using a well-defined hash function.

It does have its drawbacks though. If there have been numerous key collisions and
keys have been put very far away, the algorithm might perform poorly because it would 
have to check the value we're searching for against a good number of keys and that could be costly.

Depending on the implementation of the hashing function, the algorithm might require an array 
with the size of a huge prime number in order to avoid key collisions. This is an important thing 
to be aware of if space is of concern.
